{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586949"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:40:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:40:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15110"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15110"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.33,0.04,0.2,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7798"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80775"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7798"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66094"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7199"},{"type":"tags","id":"7200"},{"type":"tags","id":"8134"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19020"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27592"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80775"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gag reflex is an involuntary reflex which involves contraction of the pharyngeal muscles and elevation of the soft palate.\u00a0This reflex can be triggered\u00a0by stimulation of the base of the tongue, the tonsillar area or the posterior pharyngeal wall. This protective mechanism serves to prevent the swallowing of foreign objects and to prevent choking.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the gag reflex is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Its presence indicates intact brainstem function","It is absent in approximately one-third of healthy adults","Its absence always indicates neurological impairment","It is more commonly absent in older adults","It should be tested bilaterally in all trauma patients"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gag reflex is a protective mechanism that involves contraction of the pharyngeal muscles in response to stimulation of the posterior pharyngeal wall, soft palate, or base of tongue. While traditionally considered an important neurological sign, research has shown significant variation in its presence among healthy individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is absent in approximately one-third of healthy adults\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Studies have demonstrated that up to 37% of healthy individuals lack a gag reflex, making it an unreliable indicator of neurological function when assessed in isolation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIts presence indicates intact brainstem function\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because while the reflex involves brainstem pathways, its presence alone does not confirm intact brainstem function. Other brainstem reflexes and clinical findings must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIts absence always indicates neurological impairment\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect given the high prevalence of absent gag reflexes in the healthy population. The absence of a gag reflex should be interpreted in conjunction with other clinical findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is more commonly absent in older adults\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as age has not been shown to be a significant factor in gag reflex presence or absence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt should be tested bilaterally in all trauma patients\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as routine testing of the gag reflex is not recommended in trauma assessment unless there are specific concerns about brainstem function or swallowing ability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gag reflex is mediated by cranial nerves IX (glossopharyngeal) and X (vagus). When assessing brainstem function, multiple reflexes should be tested, including pupillary, corneal, and vestibulo-ocular reflexes, along with assessment of respiratory pattern and level of consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The gag reflex is absent in up to 37% of healthy individuals and its presence or absence alone should not be used to assess neurological status.","Assessment of the gag reflex tests cranial nerves IX (glossopharyngeal) and X (vagus).","Multiple other brainstem reflexes should be assessed when evaluating for neurological impairment."],"references":["Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Sivakumar S, Prabhu A. Physiology, Gag Reflex. [Updated 2023 Mar 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554502/","Bassi GS, Humphris GM, Longman LP. The etiology and management of gagging: a review of the literature. J Prosthet Dent. 2004 May;91(5):459-67. doi: 10.1016/S0022391304000939. PMID: 15153854."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66094"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15110"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66094"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T08:08:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T08:09:47+10:30"}